---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved

const data = {
  metaTitle: 'Asset Management & Maintenance Scheduling Platform — All Webbed Labs',
  metaDescription: 'How we helped a Victorian local council replace fragmented Excel-based asset tracking with a platform covering 3,800 assets — cutting emergency repair costs by 34%, giving field teams mobile access, and compressing compliance reporting from 3 weeks to 4 hours.',
  industry: 'Government',
  tags: ['React', 'Flutter', 'Node.js', 'PostgreSQL', 'Mapbox'],
  title: 'Asset Management & Maintenance Scheduling Platform',
  summary: 'A large Victorian local council was managing 3,800 assets worth $240M across multiple Excel spreadsheets maintained by different teams, with field staff phoning in issues and compliance reporting taking three weeks every quarter. We built a web and mobile platform that put every asset on a map, gave field teams their own app, and compressed quarterly reporting to four hours.',
  heroImageDescription: 'Mapbox-based asset map showing the council\'s road, parks and drainage infrastructure with condition rating colour coding, alongside the Flutter mobile app open on a field technician\'s tablet showing a maintenance job with photo capture',

  clientOverview: 'A large outer suburban local council in Victoria, covering a mix of established suburbs and new growth corridors. The council manages approximately 3,800 assets including roads and footpaths, parks and open spaces, council buildings and facilities, fleet vehicles, and stormwater and drainage infrastructure, with a total estimated replacement value of $240 million. Asset management is a core function under the Local Government Act 2020 (Vic) and the council had obligations around an Asset Management Strategy and annual reporting to the state government.',
  clientSize: 'Council with ~400 staff; asset management team of 22 across 4 functional groups',
  clientLocation: 'Outer Melbourne suburban, VIC',

  pullQuote: 'We predicted and prevented two major asset failures in the first year. The early warning system paid for the entire platform in avoided emergency repair costs on its own. Everything else is a bonus.',
  pullQuoteAuthor: 'Manager, Infrastructure and Assets',
  pullQuoteRole: 'Victorian Local Council',

  challenge: [
    'The council\'s asset management function was fragmented across four teams — roads and drainage, parks and open spaces, buildings and facilities, and fleet — each of which maintained its own spreadsheet. The spreadsheets did not share a consistent structure, did not use consistent asset identifiers, and were updated at different cadences by different staff members. There was no master list. When the Director of Infrastructure needed a complete picture of the council\'s asset portfolio, compiling it required gathering spreadsheets from four teams and reconciling them manually — a process that took days and produced a result that was out of date by the time it was complete.',
    'Field maintenance teams operated without digital tools. Technicians identified issues during patrol rounds and phoned them in to a coordinator, who logged them in the relevant team\'s spreadsheet. This created several problems. The time between identifying an issue and logging it varied from an hour to several days depending on workload. The field technician\'s observations — precise location, condition assessment, photographic record — were either lost in the telephone relay or not captured at all. Maintenance history for individual assets was incomplete because not all historical work had been logged, and because the spreadsheet structures made it difficult to link individual maintenance events to specific assets reliably.',
    'Reactive maintenance was costing the council significantly more than preventive maintenance — a well-understood dynamic in infrastructure management, but one the council had not been able to address because it lacked the asset condition data needed to schedule preventive work systematically. Without knowing the current condition of assets and their rate of deterioration, maintenance scheduling was essentially reactive by default: fix things when they break. The council\'s finance team estimated reactive maintenance was costing approximately 40% more per unit of work than planned preventive maintenance, but that estimate was itself an approximation because the cost attribution to individual assets was unreliable.',
    'State government compliance reporting under the Local Government (Performance Reporting) Framework required the council to submit quarterly asset management performance data. Producing this report took the asset management team three weeks every quarter — two weeks of data gathering from the four team spreadsheets, one week of compilation and validation. The three-week timeline meant the data in the report was already a month old by the time it was submitted. On two occasions, the council had needed to request an extension from the Department of Transport and Planning due to data quality issues identified during compilation. Both occasions resulted in formal correspondence that the Director was keen not to repeat.',
    'The absence of an early warning system for end-of-life assets was a risk that the Manager of Infrastructure had been raising in budget submissions for three consecutive years without success. The council had several major assets — a sports pavilion built in the 1980s, a drainage culvert under a major road, three heritage footbridges — that were approaching the end of their design life with no systematic monitoring of their condition. An unexpected failure in any of these would have been expensive in direct repair costs, potentially more so in consequential liability, and politically damaging if it involved public safety.',
  ],

  whyUs: [
    'The council ran an expression of interest process, receiving responses from eight vendors including three established asset management platform providers and five custom development firms. We were one of the custom development firms. In the evaluation, the council\'s assessment panel scored us highest on two criteria: technical approach to the mobile field application, and our understanding of the Local Government Act 2020 (Vic) asset management obligations.',
    'The established platform providers offered more features out of the box, but the council\'s evaluation noted that their mobile applications were designed for tablet-based data entry in conditions where connectivity was reliable — which did not describe the council\'s outer suburban geography, where some parks and drainage infrastructure were in areas with poor mobile coverage. We proposed building the field app in Flutter with offline-first data synchronisation, which was a direct response to the connectivity problem. The other custom development firms had not identified this as a consideration in their responses.',
    'We had also done prior work with a council in regional Victoria on a smaller infrastructure project, and the reference contact was a member of the assessment panel\'s extended network. The reference described us as technically capable and honest about scope — specifically that when scope changes arose during the engagement, we raised them early and clearly rather than absorbing them silently and recovering costs elsewhere. In a government procurement context, that kind of reference is valuable.',
  ],

  approach: [
    'Discovery involved four separate parallel workstreams — one with each of the four asset management teams — because their workflows, data structures and priorities were significantly different. We ran workshops with each team independently before a combined session where we surfaced the conflicts and inconsistencies between their approaches and facilitated agreement on common data standards. This was the most politically sensitive part of the engagement: asking four teams who had developed their own approaches over years to adopt a common standard required the Manager of Infrastructure to be actively present and to make decisions when consensus could not be reached.',
    'The asset taxonomy — the classification of asset types, sub-types, condition rating scales and maintenance categories — took three weeks to finalise and required a working group that included staff from all four teams plus the council\'s finance team (because asset depreciation calculations depend on asset classification). We engaged a specialist asset management consultant to peer-review the taxonomy before we built the database schema, because getting this wrong would undermine the data quality that the compliance reporting required.',
    'The IoT sensor question required careful scoping. The council had expressed interest in IoT condition monitoring for selected high-value or high-risk assets, but had not done the prior technical assessment needed to specify what sensors, what data and what integration approach were appropriate for each asset type. We proposed a two-stage approach: build the platform with an IoT integration interface defined but not connected, and run a separate sensor pilot in parallel. This meant we were not blocking the platform build on sensor decisions that were still being evaluated, and the council was not committing to sensor technology before they understood the platform architecture.',
    'We gave significant attention to the mobile application design before writing code. Field technicians were the users whose buy-in was most critical — and most at risk. A mobile app that was slower than phoning in a report would not be used. We ran a two-day design sprint with a group of six field technicians, paper-prototyping the core job logging workflow and timing it against the current phone-based process. The field technicians\' feedback shaped the application design more than any other input: they wanted speed above all else, followed by reliability in areas with no signal, followed by the ability to attach photos. Everything else was secondary.',
  ],

  solution: [
    'The platform has two main components: a web application for the asset management and administrative teams, and a Flutter mobile application for field staff. Both connect to the same Node.js API and PostgreSQL database hosted on AWS in the Sydney region.',
    'The web application\'s primary view is an interactive map built on Mapbox, showing all 3,800 council assets as geo-located points with colour coding by condition rating and asset type. Clicking any asset opens its full record: asset type and specification, installation date, expected end-of-life date, current condition rating, maintenance history, any active work orders, and the IoT sensor readings where sensors are installed. The map view was specifically requested by the infrastructure management team, who wanted to be able to see spatial patterns in asset condition — a road corridor with multiple degrading assets tells a different story than isolated instances.',
    'Asset condition is rated on a standardised five-point scale, consistent with the IPWEA (Institute of Public Works Engineering Australasia) condition rating framework that the council\'s asset management obligations reference. Each asset has a baseline condition rating entered during the data migration from the legacy spreadsheets, and the condition rating is updated when maintenance is performed or a condition inspection is conducted. The platform calculates a deterioration trajectory for each asset based on its type, age and condition rating history, and flags assets projected to cross a threshold condition rating within a configurable forward window. This is the early warning system.',
    'The Flutter mobile application runs on both iOS and Android, targeting the council-issued Android tablets that field staff carry. The app is fully offline-capable — technicians can log maintenance activities, create new defect reports, update asset condition ratings and take photos in areas with no mobile coverage, and the data synchronises automatically when connectivity is restored. The sync uses a last-write-wins conflict resolution strategy for most fields, with a conflict-flagging exception for condition ratings — if two technicians have rated the same asset differently while offline, the system surfaces both ratings for a supervisor to resolve rather than silently overwriting one.',
    'Work order management is built into the platform rather than managed externally. Maintenance tasks are created from defect reports submitted by field staff (or identified by the early warning system), assigned to a technician or crew, scheduled, and tracked through to completion. When a work order is completed, the technician marks it done from their mobile app, attaches completion photos, and the asset\'s maintenance history is updated automatically. The scheduler can see all open work orders across all teams in a single view, which enabled the consolidation of maintenance runs that was previously impossible when each team had its own task list.',
    'State government compliance reporting is generated automatically from the platform\'s data. The reporting dashboard is configured to the specific metrics required by the Local Government Performance Reporting Framework, pulling live data and generating the submission-ready report in the correct format. For quarterly reports, what previously took three weeks of manual compilation takes approximately four hours — most of that time is a data quality review by the Manager of Infrastructure rather than actual compilation.',
    'The IoT sensor integration, completed in a follow-on engagement, connects sensors installed on four high-priority assets — the drainage culvert, one heritage footbridge, and two buildings — to the platform via MQTT. Sensor readings (vibration, moisture, structural deflection where applicable) are ingested every 15 minutes and stored against the asset record. Threshold alerts are configured for each sensor type and generate work orders and notifications automatically when exceeded. The two major asset failures predicted and prevented in year one both came through this sensor alerting system.',
  ],

  implementation: [
    'The data migration from four Excel spreadsheets to a structured database was the most labour-intensive part of the project. We built a migration toolset that the asset management team used to review, classify and import their existing records. The process took six weeks and involved the four teams working through their spreadsheet data asset by asset, standardising classifications, resolving inconsistencies between teams\' records of shared assets (there were 47 assets that appeared in more than one team\'s spreadsheet, sometimes with conflicting condition ratings), and making a deliberate decision about which records were reliable enough to import and which should be entered fresh after a field inspection.',
    'The mobile app rollout followed a phased approach by team. The roads and drainage team — who had the highest volume of field activity and the most experienced mobile technology users — went first. This gave us a real-world stress test of the offline synchronisation before rolling out to teams whose field operations were less intensive. The parks team\'s experience in the second wave surfaced a photo upload issue in areas where connectivity returned intermittently, causing incomplete photo attachments. We fixed this before the buildings and fleet teams received their devices.',
    'Field staff training was conducted as half-day on-site sessions. We used the council\'s own test data — actual assets near the training location — so that technicians were using the app on familiar ground. The most common support question in the first two weeks was about what to do when the app showed a conflict on an asset condition rating — a question that indicated the sync conflict resolution was working correctly, not that it was broken. We added a plain-language in-app explanation of the conflict resolution process that reduced these questions significantly.',
    'The parallel-running period — where the old spreadsheets were still maintained alongside the new platform — lasted eight weeks rather than the six we had planned, because the roads team identified three assets in the platform data that they could not reconcile with their physical records. Investigating those three assets took longer than anticipated and turned out to surface a genuine gap in the council\'s asset register: two assets that existed physically but had never been formally recorded. These were added to the register before the spreadsheets were retired.',
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    'The asset taxonomy development was the most underestimated part of the engagement. We had scoped three weeks. It took six, and required the Manager of Infrastructure to intervene on four occasions when working group consensus broke down. The root cause was that the different teams had developed genuinely different frameworks for classifying and rating assets based on their specific asset types and maintenance approaches — frameworks that made sense within each team but were not compatible with each other. Reconciling them required not just technical decisions but organisational ones. We should have scoped asset taxonomy development as a separate pre-project phase with its own governance, rather than treating it as a discovery deliverable.',
    'The offline synchronisation architecture worked well under normal operating conditions, but we encountered an edge case during a major storm event when multiple field crews were simultaneously logging damage to the same assets in offline mode. When connectivity was restored, the sync engine received a large volume of conflicting updates for the same assets in a short time window. The conflict resolution logic handled it correctly — surfacing conflicts for supervisor review rather than losing data — but the volume of conflicts that appeared simultaneously after the storm was larger than anything we had tested for. We added a bulk conflict review interface post-event that made it easier to resolve multiple conflicts at once.',
    'The condition rating deterioration model — the algorithm that generates the early warning projections — is necessarily a simplification. We implemented a standard straight-line deterioration model appropriate for the different asset type categories, based on IPWEA guidance. But real-world asset deterioration is non-linear and influenced by factors — soil type, drainage patterns, traffic loading, maintenance quality — that the platform does not fully capture. The Manager of Infrastructure understood this and described the projections as "intelligent prompts for investigation" rather than precise predictions. Communicating this clearly in the platform\'s interface — making the uncertainty visible rather than presenting projections as facts — required careful UX work.',
    'Fleet assets turned out to have a substantially different maintenance model than static infrastructure assets. Fleet vehicles are maintained on odometer intervals and service schedules rather than condition ratings and deterioration projections. We had built the platform with static infrastructure as the primary model, and extending it to fleet required adding a second maintenance scheduling paradigm. The fleet team\'s needs were met, but the extension took one sprint longer than expected. A more thorough discovery process for the fleet use case in the initial scoping phase would have surfaced this.',
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    'The IoT sensor integration, which had been parked during the initial build, was completed in a follow-on engagement eight months after the platform go-live. Four priority assets were selected for sensor installation based on the early warning system\'s condition projections and the council\'s risk assessment. The sensor data integration was straightforward given the interface we had designed into the platform for it. The two major asset failures that were predicted and prevented — a drainage culvert showing abnormal moisture readings and a sports pavilion with progressive structural deflection — both involved sensor alerts that triggered early investigation.',
    'The council subsequently asked us to add a public-facing asset reporting portal — a simplified interface where residents can report issues with council assets (potholes, damaged playground equipment, broken footpath sections) that routes directly into the work order system. This was a significant extension of the platform\'s scope but required relatively modest additional development on the back end; the main work was the public-facing interface and the triage logic for incoming resident reports.',
    'The platform has been referenced in the council\'s State of the Assets report — the annual public document the council publishes under its Asset Management Strategy obligations — as the data source for asset condition statistics. Having the platform cited in a public statutory document has been useful for the council in demonstrating to its community that it is managing public assets responsibly, and has been a useful reference for our own business development conversations with other Victorian councils.',
  ],

  resultsNarrative: 'The 34% reduction in emergency repair costs after twelve months is the number that justified the investment in the council\'s annual report. But the change that the asset management team values most is simpler: they can answer questions about their asset portfolio. What is the condition of our footbridge network? Which drainage assets are approaching end of life in the next three years? What is the maintenance history on the sports pavilion that had a near-miss last summer? These questions used to take days to answer. Now they take minutes. That shift in operational visibility changes how the team plans, how it budgets, and how it responds when something goes wrong.',

  metrics: [
    { value: '34%', label: 'Reduction in emergency repair costs', context: 'After 12 months of platform operation; shift from reactive to preventive maintenance scheduling' },
    { value: '2.5 hrs/day', label: 'Field team data entry time saved', context: 'Per field team; across 8 teams represents approximately 20 hrs/day freed from manual phone-based reporting' },
    { value: '3,800', label: 'Assets with complete digital profiles', context: 'Including condition ratings, maintenance history and end-of-life projections — first complete asset register in council history' },
    { value: '91%', label: 'Preventive maintenance completion rate', context: 'Up from 54% under the reactive-default approach; measured against scheduled maintenance plans' },
    { value: '4 hrs', label: 'Quarterly compliance report generation', context: 'Down from 3 weeks of manual compilation for the Local Government Performance Reporting Framework submissions' },
    { value: '2', label: 'Major asset failures predicted and prevented', context: 'In year one of IoT sensor integration; both identified through condition threshold alerts before failure' },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: 'React', reason: 'Web application for the asset management team — map-based asset portfolio view, work order management and reporting dashboard' },
    { name: 'Flutter', reason: 'Cross-platform mobile app for field technicians — offline-first with background sync for areas with poor coverage' },
    { name: 'Node.js', reason: 'Backend API, maintenance scheduling engine, IoT data ingestion, and automated compliance report generation' },
    { name: 'PostgreSQL', reason: 'Spatial-capable relational database for the complex asset, condition and maintenance data model' },
    { name: 'Mapbox', reason: 'Interactive geo-mapping of 3,800 assets with custom layer styling for condition rating visualisation' },
    { name: 'AWS (EC2 + RDS + S3)', reason: 'Sydney-region hosting; S3 for field inspection photos, document attachments and report archives' },
    { name: 'IoT Sensor Integration (MQTT)', reason: 'Real-time sensor data ingestion from condition monitoring devices on priority assets' },
    { name: 'Offline Sync Engine', reason: 'Custom conflict-resolution synchronisation for field mobile app operations in low or no connectivity areas' },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
